<div class="entry-content primary-content-column columns small-12 medium-8">
<p>Life in the United States &mdash; the richest country in world history &mdash; doesn&rsquo;t need to be like this. This country&rsquo;s endless wars, deaths of despair, rising mortality rates and out-of-control gun violence did not come out of nowhere. In this second installment from an exclusive transcript of a conversation aired on <a href="https://www.alternativeradio.org/products/chon256/"><em>Alternative Radio</em></a>, public intellectual Noam Chomsky discusses the roots of gun culture, militarism, economic stagnation and growing inequality in the U.S. Read the first installment of this interview here: &ldquo;<a href="https://truthout.org/articles/noam-chomsky-trump-is-trying-to-exploit-tension-with-iran-for-2020/">Noam Chomsky: Trump Is Trying to Exploit Tension With Iran for 2020.</a>&ldquo;</p>
<p><strong>David Barsamian:</strong> <strong>Do you ever make the connection between the external violence of the U.S. state and what is happening internally with all the shootings and mass murders?</strong></p>
<p><strong>Noam Chomsky: </strong>The U.S. is a very strange country. From the point of view of its infrastructure, the U.S. often looks like a &ldquo;Third World&rdquo; country&hellip;. Not for everybody, of course. There are people who can say, &ldquo;OK, fine, I&rsquo;ll go in my private jet or helicopter.&rdquo; Drive around any American city. They&rsquo;re falling apart. The American Society of Civil Engineers gives the U.S. regularly a D, the lowest ranking, in infrastructure.</p><div class="truth-post-content-high  inline-callout-container" id="truth-255792"><aside class=" callout inline-callout callout--subscribe callout--dark" id="truth-255397">
<h2>The stories you care about, right at your fingertips</h2>
